title: For Sale:  Tommy Gun, 45ACP, Tribute to America’s Armed Forces Thompson
postcontent: Up for sale is a beautiful Thompson Commemorative,  The series is still open on this rifle and you can buy one through America remembers for $2995.  The gentleman that owned this piece was Airborne in Vietnam and recently passed unexpectedly.  The family now offers you the opportunity to purchase an aboulutely MINT, NEVER FIRED (the action has never been cycled  nor has a mag been inserted) Commemorative for $2100.00, or best reasonable offer.On the left side of a Tribute to America’s Soldiers Thompson, you’ll find two scenes that show the soldier and the Thompson in action. The first scene shows infantrymen landing on the beach during the D-Day invasion. Dodging a hail of bullets and artillery shells, soldiers dragged the Thompson through seawater and sand. Once they reached enemy positions, the last thing they needed was a misfire. The trusty Thompson rarely let them down. Also featured is an outline of the U.S.A. with the words, “Freedom Forever,” and a banner reading “Country Before Self,” both honoring the selfless contributions of America’s Soldiers. At the center, a soldier stands firing his Thompson.The right side of a Tribute to America’s Soldiers Thompson features an illustration of a soldier taking aim with his Thompson and banners that read, “Saluting America’s Soldiers” and “Defending Freedom”. The rest of the action on the right side of the receiver depicts scenes during WWII and the Korean and Vietnam Wars. In the North African campaign in WWII, soldiers wielded the Thompson alongside battle tanks during desert warfare. On the front lines of Korea, the soldiers distinguished themselves with the Thompson. Though the struggles and harsh conditions in Korea would push every soldier to the limit, the fighting spirit of America’s Soldiers carried on. In Vietnam, with helicopters in the background, soldiers relied on their Thompsons, often in the rice paddies and jungles.

postcontent: For sale: Black Vltor Emod commercial stockThank for looking!Copied and pasted from MidwayUSA.comThe Vltor EMOD Enhanced Modstock is an improved version of the original Modstock that incorporates all of its best attributes with some additional features desired by professional users in the field. The Clubfoot EMOD stock is 1" longer than the original design to increase the available comb space and length of pull in all positions on the buffer tube to benefit those using magnified optics in a DMR role. The stock's Rubber Buttplate has been widened and lengthened at the toe, and has a noticeable Negative Pitch that enables faster, more natural transitions from the ready to firing positions. A sturdy Metal Strike Plate resides under the buttplate for use as an impact or compliance tool, and extra Water Resistant On-Board Storage options have been added in the form of 2 Removable Side Tubes capable of holding 4 CR123 or 3 AA batteries each, as well as a smaller Hinged Door Compartment located at the toe that's large enough to accommodate 2 more AA batteries or other small spare parts/tools. The EMOD's Butterfly Adjustment Lever is positioned and contoured to the stock in such a way as to strike a nice balance between ease of activation and security to ensure that it is not inadvertently depressed until the user wants to use it. Additional features include a durable polymer construction that is impervious to the elements, an integral top-mounted sling loop, and 2 QD Sling Swivel Sockets. title: For Sale:  Inert 1902 C12 Shell German Imperial Navy Pre Nazi
postcontent: This is an inert 1902 C12 Shell Cartridge used by the German Imperial Navy in 24cm/L40 Twin Mounting guns. It was found outside a pawn shop, used as a bit of a gate post to the entrance. It was purchased from the owner when the shop closed.As you can tell in the pictures, it measures 40 5/8” tall, 10 5/8” wide across the base, and about 9 3/4” tall across the mouth. This certainly was an eye catcher at a gun show - it’s pretty heavy and I ended up pushing it around on a little plant stand with wheels.It does have a little corrosion on the brass, but it is by no means destroyed. It’s in pretty good shape for a shell that’s been around for 113 years and traveled halfway around the world.By the little I’ve been able to find about it, it was made during the reign of Alfred von Tirpitz, while he was expanding the German Fleet to 45 battleships. This is used specifically in Wittelsbach class battleships that were constructed from 1899 to 1904. The Wittlesbach class were a group of five pre-dreadnought battleships. After dreadnought battleships became mainstay, the armament for these ships was disassembled and used on locomotives. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_German_Navyhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wittelsbach-class_battleship#Armament
